In Bamboo 4.4.5 if the "Anonymous Users" access is unchecked from the Plan permissions page, Bamboo doesn't trigger the plans and branches when there is a change committed to t he configured repository. This works fine in Bamboo 4.3. 

The workaround is to use the following command in the postCommitBuildTrigger.sh script:
{code}
/usr/bin/curl -s -u username:password $remoteCall > /dev/null
{code}
instead of:
{code}
/usr/local/bin/wget --timeout=10 -t1 $remoteCall -O /dev/null
{code}
where the username:password are the username and the password of a user account that has permissions to build the plan.

https://docs.atlassian.com/bamboo/REST/4.0/

Under *Introduction to Bamboo's REST APIs* it says:

{quote}
… Currently the HTTP GET method is the only method available in the Bamboo REST API.
{quote}

However looking at the second resource in the docs:

{quote}
* http://myhost.com:8085/bamboo/rest/api/latest/server [GET]
** http://myhost.com:8085/bamboo/rest/api/latest/server/resume [POST]
** http://myhost.com:8085/bamboo/rest/api/latest/server/pause [POST]
{quote}

Error in the logs:
{code}
2013-05-24 13:00:35,054 INFO [qtp1795829092-125] [ArtifactDownloadStrategy] Connection closed while serving file: /Users/akhachatryan/Atlassian/BambooHome4.4.5/artifacts/PROJ3-SYMLINKS/JOB1/build-00004/Art/a.sh com.atlassian.bamboo.utils.FileCopier$IoOutputException: Closed
{code}

Steps to reproduce this:

 I collected artifacts and replaced the small file (a couple of bytes) from BambooHome/artifacts/../plan directory to be a huge file (more than 4 GB) with the same name. When I tried to download that file from the artifacts page, the download window showed 289 MB file (which is not the same as the original artifact file). The downloaded file was 289MB instead of 4GB.

For a very large repositories, the mercurial clone will fail unless if we add the option --uncompressed to it. At the moment, Bamboo clone does not use that option and as a result, build will fail with errors like:

{code}
stderr: transaction abort! rollback completed abort: stream ended unexpectedly (got 47958609 bytes, expected 47992245)
{code}

It will be great to have options of adding parameters to the clone.

I reproduced this behavior by configuring the following in the BamboInstall/conf/wrapper.conf file:
{code}
wrapper.logfile.maxsize=1m
wrapper.logfile.maxfiles=10
{code}
Also, I enabled SQL logging to generate a lot of logs to test and restarted Bamboo server. However, Bamboo ignored the configured parameter and the BambooInstall/logs/bamboo.log grew up to 23MB, and the BambooHome/logs/atlassian-bamboo.log started to roll over after 21MB.

When you do a REST request to the back end with artifacts expanded on a key :
#http://bamboo-01/bamboo01/rest/api/latest/result/<KEY>-JOB1-latest?os_authType=basic&expand=artifacts

it returns the expanded artifact <name>Build log</name> and there is a link associated with that artifact. That link is bad, you get a "Page not found" error. When I investigated, it seems to append a number to the log which doesnt work.

This is the link that is in the artifact's href, that doesn't work : {noformat}http://bamboo-01/bamboo01/download/<KEY>-JOB1-644/build_logs/<KEY>-JOB1-644.log{noformat}

If you remove the build number after the "download" element you get this, which works:  {noformat}http://bamboo-01/bamboo01/download/<KEY>-JOB1/build_logs/<KEY>-JOB1-644.log{noformat}

When using the Script task to write an inline script using any one of the following escaped XML characters:
- &amp;amp;
- &amp;lt;
- &amp;gt;
- &amp;quot;
- &amp;apos;

After save, when you go back to the task to edit it, those escaped XML characters are automatically unescaped. It appears to be impossible to keep and persist escaped characters. This becomes a problem when attempting to write a simple XML file that has escaped characters within an attribute - which in itself is VALID XML. The result of doing so creates an INVALID XML file. See screenshots for details.

Looking at various build task plugins, the BUILD_SUCCESSFUL_MARKER values are Strings; allowing this to be a compilable pattern would provide additional flexibility for tools that might produce multiple success patterns without requiring recompilation and/or multiple build task.

eg;

{noformat}
private static final String BUILD_SUCCESSFUL_MARKER = SystemProperty.BUILD_SUCCESSFUL_MARKER.getValue( "0 failures" );
{noformat}

The Jake task plugin I've written can make backend calls to one of two test frameworks, both producing .xml test results, but in one case, the success message is "0 failures" and in the other case is "Failures: 0". 

The only workarounds I have at this point are to either 1) develop a second task class or 2) run both through an external tool to transform the success string externally into something that can be similarly parsed.

Theoretically, but possibly more confusing, I could tie the result string in the plugin to a property parsed at task execution time that would allow me to change the detected string on a task-by-task basis, but I only think that's possible given how much time I've spent in the Bamboo plugin code.

Even better would be a mechanism to simply detect the return code from the process and consider it a success if the code is 0 and a failure if not, but that's probably not cross platform and relies heavily on the tools doing the right thing; in the end, changing the BUILD_SUCCESSFUL_MARKER from a String to a Pattern _might_ be the simplest solution.
